{
  "texts": [
    "A highly publicized study covered 27,697 patients undergoing 38.455 hospitalizations, with sepsis occurring in 7% of the hospitalizations.",
    "The Epic Sepsis Model predicted the onset of sepsis with an area under the curve of 0.63 (95% CI, 0.62-0.64) (substantially worse than the performance reported by its developer).",
    "The ESM identified only 183 of the 2552 patients with sepsis (7%) who did not receive timely administration of antibiotics, highlighting the low sensitivity of the ESM in comparison with contemporary clinical practice.",
    "The ESM also did not identify 1709 patients with sepsis (67%) despite generating alerts for an ESM score of 6 or higher for 6971 of all 38,455 hospitalized patients (18%), thus creating a large burden of alert fatigue.",
    "Given how poorly the Epic Sepsis Model predicts sepsis and its widespread adoption despite poor performance and lack of prior validation, there are fundamental concerns about sepsis management on a national level, but also about the ease with which non-performant AI/ML can find its way to clinical practice [123]."
  ]
}